In view of the foregoing, we have recommended, and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following:

Ensure that the PR, PO, and other supporting documents are properly filled-up with salient information regarding the procurement. Descriptions of the items, quantities, and unit costs must be specified. This is to make sure that the items that the suppliers shall be offering meet the quality, quantity, and costs and to avoid incurrence of expenses above the budget;


For the BAC to make certain that all procurements of drugs and medicines be supported with a certification signed by the requisitioning officer that the drug products being procured are enlisted and conform with PNDF Volume I, as well as the certifications cited in Section 9.1.3.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 to guarantee the quality, effectiveness and safety of drugs and medicines;

For the Municipal Accountant to review the completeness and validity of supporting documents before certifying the Disbursement Vouchers for payment;


To stop the awarding of procurement of medicines to suppliers whose nature of business is not related to the supply of drugs and medicines under the rules and regulations of the FDA and transact only with eligible pharmacies/ drugstores licensed/ certified by the FDA;


Upon receiving the Requests for Price Quotations and determining the supplier with lowest price quotations, the BAC should validate the eligibility documents submitted by the supplier and to conduct site inspection of the supplier’s place of business/ warehouse to confirm the availability of the items to be procured. Absence of which casts doubt on the capability of the supplier to deliver the required items; and

To strictly follow the provisions of RA No. 9184 regarding Competitive Bidding. Before resorting to Negotiated Procurement - Direct Contracting, there must be at least two (2) declarations of failure of bidding, evidenced by postings to PhilGEPS and to at least three conspicuous places, twice, and BAC Resolution declaring the failure thereof.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin the municipal accountant the following:
To exhaust all records to determine the nature of long-outstanding accounts, and confirm the nature, existence, and valuation of receivables to the obligor – agencies;
Strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2023-008 and IPSAS No. 29 on the required analysis of dormant accounts by performing the regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of the dormant accounts, and determine the concerned debtors;
To comply with all the conditions and requirements of COA Circular No. 2023-008 for the possible request for the write-off of the specified dormant receivable accounts to the Commission on Audit ; and
Provide for Allowance for Impairment on dormant accounts to reflect its recoverable value as required under IPSAS No. 29.

We have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct analysis and review the cause of discrepancy by tracing and locating the documents affecting the reciprocal accounts;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts through the preparation of Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) duly supported with documents, explanations and/or computations in order to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;
Maintain subsidiary ledger and conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to ensure that the balances of reciprocal accounts are the same at all times.

We have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Create Inventory Committee that will immediately conduct a complete physical inventory of all PPE of the Municipality following the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 to comply with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances;
Enjoin the Municipal Treasurer to maintain PCs for all the PPEs of the LGU, and to update /renew each PAR / ARE every thee years after issue or every time there is a change in accountability in accordance with MNGAS for LGU and COA Circular 2020-006;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain, update and reconcile her records and ledgers; and
Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect a more reliable balances of PPE accounts.

