Require the withholding of salaries and other emoluments in full of officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in their respective unliquidated outstanding cash advances;
Enjoin all concerned officials and employees to settle immediately their unliquidated cash advances and to strictly comply with rules/regulations on the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances per COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 82 of PD 1445; and
In the case of the unliquidated cash advance of the late Mayor Antolin, legal advice should be sought on how the LGU could impose the settlement of the cash advance through its heirs.

Municipal Treasurer to ensure that duly approved DTRs and application for leaves are attached to the payrolls before payment of salaries and wages are made ;
HRMO to verify the DTRs and application for leaves and should ensure that before the payroll sheets are forwarded to the Local Chief Executive for approval, the DTR should have been processed/ verified and initialed by the concerned Department Head ; and
Municipal Accountant should see to it that supporting documents were complete before recording the transaction in the books of accounts

Effect the termination of the contract/ refrain from renewing the contract of the consultants who failed to perform their duties and responsibilities as supported by their monthly accomplishment reports to be submitted to the HRMO of the municipality;
Stop the practice of hiring consultants for tasks which do not require expertise and that can be performed by the regular employees to avoid incurrence of additional expenditure which unfavourable to the agency;
Identify those consultants whose scope of work overlap with the functions of the other consultants because it is an indication that there is a need to reduce their number in order to avoid wastage of public funds; and
Require the consultants to submit curriculum vitae and other relevant information that would support their credentials and eligibilities in their chosen field of expertise and for the management to create a databank of the consultants’ credentials/qualifications in order to determine whether their accomplishments are conformable to their qualifications and to justify their appointment as consultants.

In view of the above noted lapses, we have recommended the following on the issues with regard to the procurement of medicines:
 That management require the supplier of noted technical requirements;
 That management or the BAC justify the non-submission of BAC Resolution recommending the method of procurement to be used as well as justify the awarding of the goods to a supplier with unknown qualification; While the following were recommended on infrastructure projects:
 That the management justify the non-submission of the documents on time. Likewise, require the Municipal Engineer to submit the needed documents for verification;
 Submit the supporting documents for the approved work extension order as well as warranty securities if any; and
 Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer require the submission of an irrevocable standby letter of credit or surety bond before the release of the 15% Mobilization Fee and Retention Money. Management was also advised to submit the required supporting documents covering the payments of gasoline, oil and lubricants, repairs and maintenance of vehicles, meals and snacks as well as for casual and contractual if any. Moreover, the MOA for the NTA projects should be provided for by management to ascertain whether the projects undertaken are compliant with the stipulations made by both parties. Lastly, we have recommended that henceforth, management prepare a checklist of documentary requirements to be included in the disbursement vouchers. The Municipal Accountant and Treasurer ensure that all documents were submitted and reviewed before any payment is to be made and that abide with the rules and regulations with regard to the procurement of medicines and infrastructure projects.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct all concerned officials and employees to settle immediately their unliquidated  cash  advances  or  best, demand  letter  should  be  issued. The
failure of those concerned to liquidate their cash advances would mean that liquidation or refund would be demanded from the officials/ employees responsible in allowing/ approving cash advances, particularly on those with cash advances approved despite the none liquidation of previous cash advances;
Require the withholding of salaries and other emoluments in full of officials and employees who are still in service effective immediately and apply the said withheld amounts in their respective unliquidated outstanding cash advances;
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and other department heads to strictly comply with rules/regulations on the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances per COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 82 of PD 1445; and
In the case of the unliquidated cash advance of the late Mayor Antolin, legal advice should be sought on how the LGU could impose the settlement of the cash advance through its heirs. In case that this remedy if futile, then those who approved and released any benefits due him, without considering the deduction of the subject cash advance, should be liable.

We have recommended the Local Chief Executive to enjoin all officials and employees to strictly observe the provisions of the Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445, Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles and COA Circular 96-004, viz:
For the officials receiving travel allowance to refrain from reimbursing gasoline/diesel and oil expenses for travels within 50-km radius from the official station;
To ensure that no government vehicle is to be used for purposes other than official business;
To stop from reimbursing gasoline/diesel, and oil when a private vehicle is used notwithstanding whether the purpose of travel is for official business; and
Refund of the payment made for gasoline, diesel, and oil is hereby recommended, else, a Notice of Disallowance will be issued.

We have recommended the management the following:
Require the consultants to submit curriculum vitae and other relevant information that would support their credentials and eligibilities in their chosen field of expertise in order to justify their appointment as consultants;
Stop the practice of hiring consultants for tasks which do not require expertise and that can be performed by the regular employees to avoid incurrence of additional expenditure which unfavourable to the agency;
Review their functions as stated in the Contract of Service and compare it with the actual duties and responsibilities they performed to ascertain whether or not the expected output/deliverables are being accomplished, otherwise the hiring is not justified; and
Identify those consultants whose scope of work overlap with the functions of the other consultants because being so is an indication that there is a need to reduce their number in order to avoid wastage of public coffers.

We have recommended the management the following:
For the GAD focal person to prepare GAD Plan and Budget pursuant to the provisions of Joint Circular NO. 2004-001 of DBM, NEDA, and NCRFW;
For the Local Chief Executive to enjoin the management to assure that GAD-related activities are integrated to the agency’s programs, projects, and activities so that the intended beneficiaries are assured of the services, protection, and other assistance that the GAD provision seeks to provide.

